–1290","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1 April 1300":"1 April 1300","1290":"1290","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lavenham, , Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"Harold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>here</i> ‘army’ + <i>weald</i> ‘ruler’. In pre-Conquest England, this was reinforced by the related Old Norse name <i>Haraldr</i>, introduced by Scandinavian settlers. The name was not at all popular in England after the Conquest, probably because of its association with the unfortunate  King Harold , killed at the Battle of Hastings in  1066 . It was used in some parts of Nottinghamshire in the 16th and 17th centuries, and revived more generally, along with a number of other Old English names, in the 19th century, when it suddenly became extremely popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Harold Cooke was born on 1 April 1300, in Moulsford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Johnathan Cooke, was 41 and his mother, Jessica Hunsberger, was 40. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Ros De Ville. He died in 1360, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1 April 1300–1360":"1. aprill 1300–1360","1275–1310":"1275–1310","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1325–1345":"1325–1345","1345–1371":"1345–1371","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1 April 1300":"1. aprill 1300","1290":"1290","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lavenham, , Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1 April 1300–1360":"1. huhtikuuta 1300–1360","1275–1310":"1275–1310","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1325–1345":"1325–1345","1345–1371":"1345–1371","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1 April 1300":"1. huhtikuuta 1300","1290":